This jar of vinegar will likely be my bane for the rest of the campaign. However, I can't bring myself to yeet it from existence with a clever deus ex machina. What bs will unfold with it next? I don't know, but I can't tear my eyes away.#DnD #dungeonmastermistakes
Never did I expect as a DM to have to seriously consider how much damage a wolf-demon should take from ingesting 5 gallons of vinegar. It's just something you can't plan for.

He manages to get the vinegar flask out. Math ensues as the player (IRL an engineer) calculates how much vinegar would flow out in 6 seconds. Calculus is involved.We determine the wolf-demon ingests over 5 gallons of vinegar.
Tonight they fought a wolf demon. The bard had been grappled, and was being used as a chew toy.Take a wild guess what happened next. Just guess.

The party had to break a control panel. The bard dumped his infinite vinegar supply on it, shorting it out and accidentally releasing the ancient mithral dragon they were supposed to contain.Somehow they survived this. Somehow.
He got sick himself drinking it, so he now does vinegar shots while on watch every night to build immunity, despite taking repeated poison damage.

Our bard took possession of it because of course the bard did.After a case of poisoning by cave mold, he now thinks everyone wants to drink vinegar. He tried to get a cavefish to drink it while the cleric and druid looked on in horror.
Dear reader, how so very wrong I was.

However, I thought "I mean, who really needs vinegar in a DnD campaign", and made that one still work. I thought it would be a one-off joke, then go in the bag of holding to be forgotten with all the other magical items (including the actually helpful ones!) they'd acquired.

I have done something very ill-advised in our current DnD campaign.A few sessions back there was a puzzle that involved infinte jars of wine, water, oil, and vinegar. I made it so the first three didn't work outside the room.

Fun add #2: I had the pleasure of citing master‚Äôs students‚Äô theses that (1) established the behavior of the ClO4-/ClO3- reductase and, my favorite, (2) plopped a CRB into a culture of PRB that accumulated lots of ClO3-. We generalize their work and start from observed communities

Fun add #1: These respiratory pathways (the only two known for Cl oxyanions) have been studied together in parallel for DECADES without anyone understanding that they interact through this mechanism and with such an effect on community structure.

The takeaway? ClO4- respiring bacteria can support large populations of ClO3- respiring bacteria by releasing large or small amounts of ClO3-. Will be interesting to know how the chemical environment constrains an interaction based on a diffused reactive compound. https://t.co/rrX8ixKx89

Using one enzyme for two substrates seemed to be a big flaw in PRB. When ClO4- >> ClO3-, ClO3- accumulates. Because the CRB enzyme does not bind ClO4-, it can use all the available ClO3- and subsequent respiratory substrates, while the PRB only gets energy from ClO4-. https://t.co/ExWIr4kdE0

To help conceptualize the results, we used a simple  model of a theoretical case: two cells completely identical except in the first enzyme of the pathway using both ClO4- and ClO3- (like a PRB) or only ClO3- (like a CRB).

Some important, unresolved Qs. How does small accumulation of an intermediate (say at 0.3 mM ClO3- from 10.0 mM ClO4-) support such a large population? How can cells with an incomplete pathway, which in theory has less total yield, DOMINATE cells with a complete pathway?

What intermediate is responsible: ClO3-, ClO2-, and O2? By deleting genes in a CRB required for using different intermediates, we found that ClO3- is the basis of the interaction. Other evidence? Some PRB accumulate small amounts of ClO3-, and CRB deplete it. https://t.co/GbNZqgN37l

We observed growth of CRB in every combination with PRB we tested. We also re-analyzed a previous study and found OTUs related to our CRB isolates were often really abundant in communities fed only ClO4-. So it's a conserved interaction between metabolisms. https://t.co/brkSNputg8

This study began when we isolated the ClO4- respiring bacteria and found a BIG surprise. Not a single ClO4- respiring bacterium but two or more bacteria: a ClO4- respiring bacterium (PRB, red) supporting a much, much larger population of ClO3- respiring bacterium (CRB, orange). https://t.co/FZbzDKAyAh

As you can see, the Cl cycle involves many molecules, both stable and reactive, that are cast about the Earth and used by life in imaginative ways. It‚Äôs a rich set of interacting parts that we still have much to learn from.

(The above image is from an upcoming preprint about ClOx-, so it emphasizes ClOx-. Most Cl is found as chloride or organic chlorine, and several excellent reviews have covered Cl cycling from the perspective of organic Cl alone).

With the reduction of HOCl to Cl-, the chlorine cycle has come full circle. Cl was changed to and from organic Cl, organic Cl was broken into volatile Cl, Cl was oxidized to ClOx- and HOCl, and those molecules were reduced to chloride. https://t.co/5Oe2RUALQV

HOCl is fairly common, so better knowledge of reactive Cl stress will help us understand how microbes live in ecosystems such as soil, wastewater treatment plants, and immune systems, and may lead to interesting new biotechnologies.

Responses to HOCl are now being discovered. Many microbes can sense HOCl and are equipped with response systems inside and outside their cells. HOCl rapidly oxidizes S groups in proteins, meaning that protein repair is very important. https://t.co/xsBGzn5H9k

ClO2- is less toxic than HOCl but still bad. Intriguingly, the enzyme chlorite:oxygen lyase is found in organisms that don‚Äôt seem to reduce ClO4- and ClO3-, suggesting ClO2- is produced by some other source at high enough concentrations to be toxic to microorganisms.

Like other oxyanions such as sulfate and nitrate, ClO4- and ClO3- can be respired by microorganisms in the absence of oxygen. To avoid making bleach, these organisms have a unique enzyme that converts chlorite (ClO2-) to Cl- and O2. https://t.co/PH7jhaOyvG

The most oxidized ClOx- compound, perchlorate (ClO4-), is so stable that it accumulates in the absence of life. Deserts have high concentrations of ClO4- as well as chlorate (ClO3-). On the surface of Mars, ClO4- can be 1% of the mass of sediment! https://t.co/R8vyrZYY19

That's because Cl in the air or ocean spray can be split by UV light (or lightning) into Cl radicals. Stratospheric Cl radicals react with O3 as a catalyst: 1 Cl molecule can consume 100,000 O3 molecules. Cl often rains down to the surface as Cl-, HCl, or small amounts of ClOx-.

Volcanism emits volatile Cl as hydrochloric acid (HCl) - but not always. In the Permian, lava bubbling through organic-rich halite (NaCl) is thought to have produced enough CH3Cl to completely destroy the ozone layer, leading to mutations caused by UV light exposure. https://t.co/TdNEzLdvr6

Small organic Cl molecules can be gaseous, like chloromethane (CH3Cl), which is a natural source of stratospheric ozone (O3) degradation. Sources and sinks of CH3Cl are being determined; respective examples are salt marshes and microbes that consume methane, a similar molecule. https://t.co/fybcVNCzJG

All this HOCl production means that lots of Cl, sometimes most of it(!), gets bound to organics. When there's no oxygen around, some microbes respire organic Cl using an enzyme called reductive dehalogenase. They help us clean up organic Cl pollution. https://t.co/ULd27F31Ey

Haloperoxidases are wild: they combine Cl- and hydrogen peroxide to make hypochlorite (HOCl), a.k.a. bleach. Some fungi use bleach's strong oxidizing power to break down plant matter. Your immune cells use bleach to kill invading pathogens. https://t.co/N8mlrsE3lY

Enzymes called halogenases and haloperoxidases make organic Cl using the chloride ion (Cl-). Cl- is stable, a major anion in salts and seawater, and therefore the ‚Äúcenter" of the Cl cycle. Cells use Cl- for various purposes, but only rarely is it used as a substrate. https://t.co/uMPi3Hu60N

All types of life synthesize organic Cl compounds. The addition of Cl makes a molecule‚Äôs shape less familiar to enzymes and therefore harder to degrade - a useful modification for chemical signaling and defense. (Many pharmaceuticals make use of that property). Some examples: https://t.co/AF3i07zdFt

For scientists further away from the field and the broad public there is a massive world of difference between epigenetics meaning non-DNA trans-generational inheritance and epigenetics meaning "I did a bisulphite experiments to track cell state".

All of this is a good science. I hang out with enough first class "epigeneticists" (including my boss, Edith Heard) to know this and usually the meaning of epigenetics is clear from context. However all of the above can and have been called "epigenetics"

(Using "epigenetics" in this non-genetic components of variance gets very confusing. Some people immediately jump to trans-generational inheritance - very rare in mammals - whereas most people want to study something very common - the non-genetic part of variation, eg biomarkers)

If you want to talk about non-genetic components of variance in phenotypes, either say "non genetic components" or spell it out "non genetic effects, such as lifestyle factors, individual choice and random choice". These effects might show up in the methylation patterns on DNA

If you have non-DNA based trans-generational inheritance, you could say "trans-generational epigenetic inheritance" though actually I think "non-DNA mediated trans generational inheritance" would be clearer (and make sure you check your F3 generation carefully!)

If you want to talk about regulatory cell state persistence through mitosis, use the phrase "persistent cell state through mitosis" - and if it is mediated you think by DNA methylation, use that. "The persistence of this regulatory state across multiple round of mitosis ..."

If you are studying parent of origin effects or X chromosome inactivation, using the words "parent of origin" or "X chromosome activation", not "epigenetics", eg "the inheritance pattern suggests that weak parent of origin effects must be moderating the penetrance..."

If you've just done an experiment using bisulphite sequencing or chip on a histone modification, use the terms "DNA methylation" or "histone modification", not "epigenetics". eg "this experiment shows that DNA methylation is correlated with gene expression..."

So watch out, would-be drive-by homophobes: this faggot is fucking tired of your shit. The shock has worn off. And he can run. And will politely but firmly make goddam sure that your people know exactly the kind of cowardly, dipshit, unaccountable homophobe you are. Fin. 15/15.
It feels good to be able to give them a small taste of consequences for their actions. I'm hoping that @NHLBruins might, perhaps, give them some more. 14/15.

He thanked me for running after them, because he - like I am - is tired of getting yelled at from cars by cowards who can't even maintain eye contact with the people they've yelled homophobic shit to on the street. Tired because it happens ALL THE TIME. 13/15.
As they drove away in complete silence, I yelled something to the effect of "Yeah, motherfuckers, drive away", and my boyfriend ran up to me and gave me a hug. 12/15.

"What did you yell at me? From your car. While I was walking down the street. Holding hands. With my boyfriend."They all turned and stared straight ahead. Completely silent.The light turned green. 11/15.

Then I also had the driver's attention. A clean-shaven blonde white guy with a Mortal-Combat-looking flat-top haircut. He and the guys in the back all had pretty built upper bodies. Maybe they play hockey... Since I had all their attention now, and a red light, I repeated. 10/15.
Then the three bros packed into the back seat saw me and stopped laughing. When I had their attention, I stared at the passenger and directly asked: "What did you yell at me?" 9/15.
I think he did, because he got really quiet, and stopped laughing. 8/15.

So I walked to the passenger side window and, from the sidewalk, made eye contact with the passenger, a skinny white guy with scraggly shoulder-length brown hair, glasses, and a facile attempt at a mustache and facial hair, and stared to see if he recognized me. 7/15.

That's when I noticed their @NHLBruins plates. The picture isn't great, but I'm happy to share it with Bruins mgmt if they're curious to know what folks repping their brand are getting up to while driving down Pleasant from Comm Ave towards Coolidge Corner around 9:09pm. 6/15.
I stood next to their shitty black Kia and took a photo of their car and license plate. They didn't notice. 5/15.
So I ran. #gayrage 4/15.

Usually when this happens, I get so flustered I can't act.  And then angry at myself for letting it happen without consequences.But then I saw that they were stopped at the light three blocks down. 3/15.

We both immediately let go of each others' hands, and my chest felt like it caved in a little, and I lost my breath, as happens every time some asshole yells something homophobic at me on the street. 2/15.

My boyfriend and I were holding hands walking home from a nice dinner date when a car full of bros drove by on Pleasant St, in Brookline, the street we live on, and yelled 'PENIS' at us out the window. 1/15.

You also have an obligation to those who will come after and try to bring more rigor to your system or technique. If you have not honestly qualified your exciting results, then you make it incredibly difficult for their important contributions to be appreciated.

This isn't about being anal. This isn't even about being rigorous. It's about being kind. If your work is useful at all, then someone (maybe future you) will eventually make a decision based on your work. You have an ethical obligation to not mislead them.
If you're presenting a method for others to use and didn't try to find its failure modes or buried them in the supplement so it would look better, then say that!
If you're using an algorithm with well known and characterized failure modes and did not check whether your use encountered those modes, then say that!
If your scoring function contains terms whose motivation and interpretation are non-probabilistic, then don't call it a probabilistic scoring function!
If your model was high precision because you used a sampling technique that was incapable of exploring conformational space, say that. If you didn't check if it explored space well, then say that.

you have no idea how good I‚Äôve become at candy crush in my absence https://t.co/2KzcEuI09H
I would like to also thank @cncurtis and both of our labs for great discussions! Please do let us know what you think - we would love to know. n/n

I am very excited about this work and for the authors. It is particular fun that this work confirmed Chris's Ph.D. work with @leonidmirny where they did argue that cancer progression is the tug of war between advantageous drivers and deleterious passengers. 23/n

So it looks like the tumors carry a large deleterious load of many likely mis-folded proteins. How do they manage this? And does this generate a key vulnerability in tumors that can be exploited therapeutically as was suggested previously?  https://t.co/FzjoWP3kbc 22/n

They showed that the data are consistent with drivers having on average ~20% advantage (which is roughly what we see in mouse models for Lkb1 loss  https://t.co/tvc8SUWZGW) and passengers having an average individual cost of ~1% and total cost of ~40%. 21/n

Having established the pattern of attenuation of efficacy of selection in the high mutation burden tumors, @SusanneTilk and @cd_mcfarland used simulations to demonstrate consistency with predictions of simple models of clonal evolution and estimated some key parameters 20/n

These patterns hold across multiple datasets, mutational calling algorithms, cancer types, and clonal and sub-clonal mutations. Similar patterns are seen in copy-number mutations. An aside - while the paper is short and readable it describes a ridiculous amount of work! 19/n

Here @SusanneTilk and @cd_mcfarland show that these predictions hold. Cancers that have very low mutational burden show strong evidence of purifying selection against passengers (~60% of replacement mutations are eliminated) and very strong positive selection for drivers. 18/n https://t.co/Z5HkruXEnX

If mutations are rare then they also rarely end up being linked and selection can notice marginal effects of mutations quite easily. If mutation rate is high, marginal effects of mutations are less important. Both purifying and positive selection become inefficient. 17/n

@cd_mcfarland and @SusanneTilk decided to test this possibility in a very clever way. It is known that selection is particularly inefficient in the absence of recombination when mutation rate is high. 16/n

The other possibility is that passengers are often quite harmful but selection can't remove them. One key possibility is the lack of recombination allows deleterious passengers to hitchhike with the drivers as long as the drivers are stronger than the passengers.  15/n

I don't see a reason why somatic cells should escape the deleterious effects of protein misfolding as long as the putatively dispensable genes are expressed in cancer. And they are. So, something does not quite make sense here. 14/n

This is a fascinating hypothesis but never seemed likely to me because most selection against germ-line protein mutations is due to their effect on folding and unrelated to  function. This was shown convincingly by @dallandrummond and colleagues https://t.co/cdRFdLBOOj 13/n

Why would this be the case? There are two possibilities. One is that these replacement mutations are neutral. They do nothing at all possibly because most genes in humans are only important for multicellular function and development and dispensable in clonal growth. 12/n

These fantastic papers from 2017 by @imartincorena and colleagues as well as Donate Weghorn and colleagues established this pattern quite clearly: https://t.co/dpSWa2WnH8 and https://t.co/GdyDsli4xm 11/n

These analyses suggested that almost none of the putatively functional, amino acid replacement mutations are  weeded out by selection in cancer unlike in germ-line evolution where the majority (often vast majority) of replacement mutations are eliminated 10/n

Passenger mutations by definition can be either neutral or harmful. So what are they in cancer? The standard approach to test this is to ask whether natural selection weeds out putatively functional passengers at a higher rate than the mutations more likely to be neutral. 9/n

The word passenger is good here as it connotes hitching a ride with a driver. This is particularly appropriate in clonal, somatic growth without recombination. Once a mutation lands on the genome of an expanding clone it got it made, even it doesn't help the expansion. 8/n

Ok, so what is the puzzle? First some background. Cancer sequencing showed that most cancers accumulate many mutations in many genes. Some of these mutations are likely to be advantageous for the tumors (they generated drivers) but many are thought to be mere passengers. 7/n

This is tame as interview stories go, but those two interactions stuck with me for a long time. Even if you don't think a candidate is up to the standards of your institution, you invited them, so treat them like they and their contributions have value.

Was seated next to the same program head at dinner. They looked at me, paused, then turned to the student on the other side and said, "You went to [other ivy league], right?" They didn't speak to me the rest of the meal. I didn't get in.

My first interview was with the head of the program, who acted like they'd rather be anywhere else. Looked at my CV and asked me about my most recent 1st author paper: "So, what is @PLOSCompBiol?" Oh, they knew.

They hadn't seen a good blue bean either, but did have some blueish seeds turn up from a random bee-made hybrid in their gardens.The seeds were black, with a hint of blue, when viewed in the right light.They kindly sent me three beans. Three magic beans.

Eventually, after a few years of trying to source the rare blueish beans I would sometimes find online, I ended up chatting with a bean collector (@UrsulaV; check them out, they do other cool things too).

I found research identifying the pigments found in various dry beans. Some black beans turn out to contain high levels of the blue-colored anthocyanin called delphinidin (named after the blue delphinium where it is also found).But still, blue doesn't really show up in beans.

I started on this venture when I learned that typical red beans are that color due to a class of pigments called anthocyanins. This same class of pigments contains variations that are blue, so I was certain that blue beans should be doable.

This is something I've spent several years trying to bring into existence. Now, technically, there are a few other "blue" dry bean varieties out there, but none I've seen have the -right- blue. Some look more purple to me. Others look more grey.I wanted something clearly blue.

Seeds from plant #3 & #4 of the blue beans project. Three other plants have not yet ripened any pods.Wait. BLUE BEANS? If you're new to following me, you might not have seen me talk about this #PlantBreeding project yet. https://t.co/RQJnqCEyrb

The original GO comprised a few thousand annotations and gene-products. Today's GO summarises the findings of 150,000 published scientific papers as 700,000 annotations. The evolving nature of GO means it's important you use the most up-to-date version! 9/9
Each gene association within GO required a citation and the type of supporting evidence was encoded into that ontology association. 8/9
GO was designed to incorporate molecules with different levels of biological knowledge, and to dynamically change as new information became available. 7/9
The original GO release described only general eukaryotic ontologies, not cell- or tissue-specific ontologies. 6/9
Their underlying motivation was the ‚Äúgrand unification of biology‚Äù (i.e. the then perhaps surprising finding of widespread orthology in the genomes of different eukaryotic model organisms). 5/9
They aimed to create a ‚Äústructured, precisely defined, common, controlled vocabulary for describing the roles of genes and gene products in any organism‚Äù. 4/9
The original Gene Ontology Consortium comprised three of the model organism databases: FlyBase, Mouse Genome Informatics (MGI), and the Saccharomyces Genome Database (SGD). 3/9
In 2000 the Gene Ontology Consortium published a paper and a freely accessible online resource to assist biologists in gene and gene-product annotation. 2/9
I've just spent a lovely hour reading the original Gene Ontology publication, because the history of bioinformatics is fun! Here is a summary of that paper. https://t.co/veIxVcqtrC 1/9

So - back to main point - I encourage you to separate "genetics" from "ethnicity" - the former is a tree like thing focused on the mechanisms of heritability around DNA - the latter is a box representing mainly cultural factors ticked by people or declared on forms.

Again, counterintuitively, we can use genetics both to trace the origin on haplotypes geographically - basically every DNA variation arose in one person in one place, and we can increasingly narrow down those locations - and at the same time observe these complex movements
but also the endless "day to day" movement of people - along trade routes, on ships, due to wanderlust or economic necessity.

Overlayed on this rapid expansion is endless movement of people - both big migrations (for example, the Yamama migration for the caucaus into Europe, mixing with the Anatolian farmers; the Anatolian farmers going both west into Europe and South down the east coast of Africa)
(it is sort of comic as a geneticist when you compare wild Homo sapiens diversity of any other wild organism - Medaka fish, fruit flies, wolves, Chimpanzees... all have higher diversity)

But this complex mixing is not something that has happened only in the last 200 years. It has happened all through human history. We are an odd species - we exploded out of Africa insanely quickly and we are remarkably *undiverse* in our genetics

Anyone who has recent complex mixture parents with different skin colours who might get the phrase "Mixed race" (whatever that means!) has to navigate this all the time, decide how to present themselves, answer these questions and which box on forms to tick.

... skin colour triggers labelling, pigeon hole construction and often questions about heritage/ancestry. There is no good reason why. The Black British in Liverpool have visibly coloured skin but really are as British as myself - not just *culturally* but in terms of ancestors

This feels "obvious" for height - we don't wander around asking tall people if they have some Estonia heritage - and pretty obvious for hair colour, though red hair does have association with the Celtic fringe of Europe (but again, is not a topic for early questions) but ...

This gives rise to the first cross current; although height, skin colour, hair colour are *genetic*, knowing someones height, skin colour or hair colour tells you very little about the rest of someone's genome.

Second is that the genetic loci behind these characteristics is a minority of the genome - height has the most "footprint" - skin colour is quite a lot smaller (though skin colour genetics is complex inside these loci) and hair colour also small.

Two important things about these sorts of characteristics; first genetics is a big part of the variation of these physical characteristics - your height / skin colour is well predicted as the average of your parents (notice - averaging from two!).

Skin colour - the main human feature to characterise ethnicity - is just another phenotype that humans have; you can put it alongside hair colour (where it share some genes), height and other physical characteristics.

A common place view is to place ethnicity as a sort of "crude" unsophisticated view point on genetics - many people map discovery about genetics to their perception of ethnicity, as if genetics and ethnicity are somehow equivalent at some level of granularity. Not true.

Trying to get a perspective on genetics and ethnicity is hard - ethnicity is so deeply wired into societies that its existence, basis and rationale is often not questioned - it just "is". But it is more complex, messy and warping than this

(Even if you were really mean and hard nosed, and only wanted to benefit the "UK / US / DE / developed country population" sub Saharan genetics would still be a no-brainer - all sorts of reasons, from cosmopolitan diverisity in cities to classifying benign variants due to freq.)

Sub saharan African genetics (done by and with African scientists) is a no-brainer - more alleles, tighter mapping, more equitable health and research. This is a win-win-win situation and we should just ... do more of this!

I will also be talking about the need for more sub Saharan genetics studies, but from my perspective this is really about supporting scientifically and lobbying financial support for projects like @H3Africa which is delivering on this.

These are ...not the same things... critically - there are *a lot* of self identified Europeans with clear European ancestry - for starters basically all of Finland and most of Sardinia - who never fall into the PC1/PC2 blob but it's far easier to write down the shorter terms.

However in genetics we still need some words to describe what we do, and sometimes we borrow the everyday ethnicity words, eg "European Ancestry" to describe a scientific concept, eg "the well mixed sub part of the sample from PC1 and PC2 in a principal component analysis"
This complexity grows as we discover more about population history (all ages), much of which is being illuminated by DNA sequencing (both of people now and ancient bones)

But that's the "now" part - it was as complex and mixed in the forced slavery and migrations of colonialism, and as mixed and complex in Hun migrations or the Yamama migration of Asia into Europe, or the Bantu migrations through Africa

But this confidence in ticking a box is as mainly cultural, not genetic - genetics is far more complex, with complex movements in pre-history, in history and right now. Anyone who lives in London, New York, Nairobi, Lagos, San Paulo knows this by just their friends and neighbours

It goes also to the fact that this "confident box ticking when presented with a series of ethnic group choices" does seem to run in families - if parents had a confident box to tick the children also are confident on the same boxes.

Most people find this counterintuitive (I did for a long time) - ethnic groups feel quite solid and well defined - people often are confident of which box they should tick (though by no means everyone - many people just don't fit in the boxes).

What do I mean by this? Underlying ethnicity terms is the concept that there are relatively well defined groupings of people and that these groups have distinct genetic components. This model is both clearly not right and, more importantly, not useful.

Other aspects of my research include genetic analyses to evaluate population health via parameters like genetic diversity. This can give us a better idea of how roseate tern populations have changed over time, since we don‚Äôt have historical records from the Caribbean. https://t.co/Wo5EXDr5rE

We‚Äôre seeing this around the world, as globally seabirds have declined by ~70% since 1950. Declines are mainly due to overfishing & habitat loss, but as numbers dwindle & invasive species spread, nest predation is becoming a bigger contributing factor https://t.co/e4oCpMgFpT

Seabirds avoid predation by nesting in big colonies on small islands. A little nest predation doesn‚Äôt matter when colonies are so big‚Äîthe ‚Äúswamping‚Äù effect. With major seabird declines of the 20th century, this dynamic is changing. A little predation can have a big impact now. https://t.co/waJbqjIG7k

Results are in: lots of things eat roseate tern eggs & chicks. Mostly native species like yellow-crowned night-herons, red-tailed hawks, & crabs, but some of the cays have invasive rats that can wipe out entire colonies in weeks. They gotta go. https://t.co/B1E2vQ7tSl

1st step: evaluate nest success. Tricky, bc in the VI roseate terns switch colony sites yearly, & they have a lot of cays to choose from. We can‚Äôt visit these remote colonies regularly, so we use game cameras to monitor nests & evaluate nest predation. https://t.co/za4ol4RZ6t

** Climate and Weather are NOT the same things. Climate Scientists use very different model and study long-term trends in a very different way. Chaos theory makes accurate predictions of the weather difficult but does NOT undermine consensus of climate predictions.

* Others have mentioned statistics and probability in response to this but we must bear in mind that this isn‚Äôt the only source of error and doubt in modelling and predictions. I hope this shows that chaos theory affects our daily lives.

This doesn‚Äôt take complex expertise to understand. I‚Äôm not a meteorologist. This is all underpinned by undergraduate level mathematics. Of course people in power should also trust experts if they cannot understand it themselves.

We‚Äôve all experienced this and have an initiative understanding of the results. That‚Äôs why we have updated weather forecasts and many people check them regularly. This is a major application of supercomputing because forecasting far enough in advance to give warnings is hard.

Our predictors will get far worse, the further out we go. That‚Äôs why it‚Äôs often accurate over a scale of hours or days but not weeks. Anything more than 7-10 days out is pure speculation. We cannot know with any degree of accuracy, what the actual weather will turn out to be.

Even with the most accurate modern weather monitoring equipment and the world‚Äôs most powerful supercomputers, we cannot avoid this effect, only reduce it. This is why weather forecasts have gotten better but are still unreliable and subject to change.

What matters here is *measurement error*, even a small error in measuring current weather states will lead to large differences between what we can predict and what actually happens. We cannot know the true state of the system and our approximations will get exponentially worse.

The weather is the original textbook example of this. Chaos theory was discovered *by a meteorologist* in the 1960s. The well-known Lorentz equations are based on these weather models. Modern weather models are even more complicated but are still chaotic.https://t.co/SLyu4nSdeI https://t.co/M2s5t5RY3x

What this means in reality is that we need to know the EXACT values of the current state of the system for the models predictions to be accurate, even if the model is perfect. This is impossible for the weather as we cannot measure it this accurately for the entire planet.

This is because a chaotic system has, by definition, such complex dynamics that even a tiny difference in the current state of the system will have huge consequences for the future. A small change could result in big differences in the future (known as the ‚Äúbutterfly effect‚Äù).

The reason for this is *chaos theory* which most people have heard of but often misunderstand. This isn‚Äôt about probability and uncertainty. A chaotic is deterministic, it will always end up at a predetermined future state but it‚Äôs *really hard* to know what that will be.

To conclude: We tried to fix some of the problems in Lactobacillus taxonomy using public genome data.It's amazing what you can do with public data only and big kudos to @S_Wittouck for involving me in this awesome project.

Finally, we identified 8 clusters for which we could not assign a species name. We conclude that these are novel Lactobacillus species, although they were already uploaded by someone to a public genome database.

However, ten clusters contained type genomes from two or three different species, indicating that these species should be merged.Contrary we also found that Lactobacillus aviarius has two subspecies detected in two genome clusters indicating that this species should be split.

This led to 239 genome clusters (~de novo species) which were then compared to the current taxonomy. The majority of them (200) contained type genomes from exactly one species showing that for them taxonomy is in line with our genome-based taxonomy.

However, the species level was excluded on the GTDB and it was known that within the genus Lactobacillus, some problems were present. That's why we downloaded every genome associated with the Lactobacillus Genus Complex and reclassified them using their core nucleotide identity.

Nowadays, taxonomic identification of bacteria is shifting towards genome-based metrics instead of e.g. the 16S rRNA gene. A great example is the Genome Taxonomy Database (https://t.co/mVxZNTMo8e) which has reclassified all Bacteria and Archeae based on genomics.

Validation rules are gradually being added to databases on https://t.co/eMF5DsTyMO as we try to make the job of curators easier.
This can help reduce the entry of contradictory information, such as if a bacterial isolate is from blood or CSF, then the disease field value must reflect invasiveness and not a carrier state.
Now, rules can be defined that further constrain fields based on values, or whether values have been entered, for one or more other fields. https://t.co/jVJq1yhdu7
It has always been possible to constrain field values based on data type, min/max ranges, lists of allowed values and even regular expressions.

As a reviewer, I suggested that was fishy, and suggested 3 new analyses, as part of a-3 page review of my thoughts. The paper was rejected.Now, I see the paper published elsewhere, with those individuals simply removed, and data being very "conclusive".

Last year I reviewed a manuscript and I noticed some fishy trends in the data - one set of individuals seemed to contradict the authors' statements and hypotheses (and the central message of the manuscript).

Nevertheless, data is data; we've done now enough positive controls of methods, phenotypes and other things to rule out all sorts of crude issues; if there is something we've missed, it is subtle, so we .... are ready.

Again, there is oddly more scrutiny and methodological angst about this sort of stuff for these social reasons (this finding doesn't fit what we thought we knew) so ... feels a bit like walking uphill *all the time*.

Finally there is a social part; if it is relatively common feeling that X does indeed cause Y, but we need to tidy up some details, then one has the long road of persuading first your collaborators and then the collaborator has to persuade a broader set of people to reverse.

It's also frustrating because it is harder to show "is not associated" - both philosophically about rejection of hypotheses but also in the mundane business of wanting to get tight confidence intervals around an effect size estimate.

Part of the frustration is that the "narrative" part of science is easier with positive results (X causes Y because...) where as X doesn't cause Y can feel a little silly in that there are alot of X's which wont cause Y (In this case, people had good reasons to think X causes Y)

Just had one of those moments in science when one has to take a *negative* result (pretty clearly not seeing any effect of X on Y) as *as interesting* as a positive result - it closes out options, provides information, but it is frustrating to deal with

Major fringe benefit of working with dogs is that their owners love to share happy pics during remission (shared with permission). https://t.co/PyEHBHtSEn

1 of our most exciting findings was that diet-induced remission was associated w/ a bile acid (BA)-producing Clostridium species, C. hiranonis. We isolated this organism from multiple remission cases and showed that it stabilizes BA levels and reduces GI disease in a mouse model.

We also show that diet-induced remission in both dogs and humans is associated with increased secondary bile acid synthesis. So we decided to go after the potential producers of these important metabolites.

So what did we find?  First, we observed rapid remission in about 60% of animals treated with diet - a remission rate that closely matches that which has been observed in pediatric #Crohns patients treated with exclusive enteral nutrition

This was a huge amount of work that involved a 4yr clinical study in dogs, longitudinal #microbiome assays, assembling a collection of canine microbial isolates, and in vivo mouse experiments w/ these isolates.  @wslvri is the fantastic postdoc that led the charge on this project

Why dogs?  b/c they naturally develop GI disease that shares many features with human IBD. But...importantly (and unlike humans), diet can be strictly controlled in dogs, and prescription diets have long been standard of care in #vetmed
